image.altText: An illustration depicting vials of red liquid, a man walking with a duffel bag and sheets of paper flying through the air.

props.synopsis: Vials of replica weight loss drugs Ozempic and Mounjaro are being illegally shipped across the world from a house on the outskirts of Sydney.

title.children: Red vials of replica Ozempic are being illegally shipped around the world. We tracked down the Sydney man behind it

image.altText: Russian President Vladimir Putin chairs a meeting with members of the government

props.synopsis: One of Vladimir Putin's fiercest critics calls on Australia and other Western nations to declare his leadership illegitimate following a Russian presidential election that was widely considered a sham.

title.children: 'He is a criminal': The push for Western leaders to declare Vladimir Putin 'illegitimate'

image.altText: Treasurer Jim Chalmers stands in a corridor holding a coffee cup in dark early morning light

props.synopsis: If the Fair Work Commission delivers a minimum wage rise at or above inflation, how would it change the RBA's decision about when or whether to cut interest rates?

title.children: What does the government really think about the economy? We'll find out in the budget

image.altText: Richard Scolyer

props.synopsis: Professor Richard Scolyer took courageous steps as a cancer researcher, becoming a guinea pig for a radical experiment. And the results could spell the biggest breakthrough in 20 years.

title.children: 'It's a no-brainer': Ten months on, Richard Scolyer is defying the odds and creating a legacy

image.altText: Armani Francois

props.synopsis: The day-to-day lives of children in Alice Springs are being impacted by the town's youth curfew, on the brink of school holidays.

title.children: Armani was stopped by police during curfew while getting a burrito. She says it was 'intimidating'

image.altText: Front on view of an icebreaker ship.

props.synopsis: When the RSV Nuyina was first launched in 2021, the vessel was described as a "Disneyland for scientists". But, three years, and several PR disasters, later, the $528 million ship is yet to undertake a science voyage.

title.children: It's billed as a 'Disneyland for scientists'. But $528 million icebreaker hasn't yet been on a science voyage

image.altText: A man standing near his unfinished home

props.synopsis: Steve Yates is just one of many aspiring home owners who have been left in limbo as the state's insurance authority deals with a backlog of collapsed builders.

title.children: Steve's builder went bust three years ago. His home is still just 80pc finished

image.altText: A mother standing outside a home holding her baby and next to her young son

props.synopsis: Government Services Minister Bill Shorten says 3,000 new Service Australia workers will help sort the backlog of claims and relieve long call wait-times, as benefit recipients say the system is too complex and slow.

title.children: This English teacher has no idea how anyone with less help is navigating Centrelink

image.altText: A young man with dark hair, a beard, a suit and glasses walks on the street.

props.synopsis: Network Ten applies for a last-minute application to introduce new evidence in Bruce Lehrmann's defamation case against the company and its journalist Lisa Wilkinson, just days before the judgement was due to be handed down.

title.children: Network Ten makes eleventh-hour application to introduce new evidence in Bruce Lehrmann defamation case

image.altText: The vascular system of a piece of wood infested by shot hole borer beetles

props.synopsis: The polyphagous shot-hole borer is destroying trees in Perth's iconic parks, and there are fears it could cause an economic disaster should it cross the Nullarbor.

title.children: 'It's devastating': A tiny pest is ruining Perth trees and could cause an economic disaster if it spreads east

image.altText: A beach with white sand, with the ocean on the left and dunes on the right.

props.synopsis: The 36-year-old man slipped from rocks in Cape Arid National Park on Saturday afternoon and has not been seen since. Meanwhile, a woman has been rescued by a bystander near Albany.

title.children: Search suspended for man who fell off rocks in remote WA national park, while woman is rescued near Albany

image.altText: King Charles shakes a woman's hand while walking next to Queen Camilla.

props.synopsis: King Charles makes his first public appearance since announcing his cancer diagnosis alongside Queen Camilla on Easter Sunday.

title.children: 'He is looking very well': King Charles makes first public appearance since announcing cancer diagnosis

image.altText: Pope Francis stands on a balcony with two men either side of him and pink and white flowers in front of him.

props.synopsis: In his address at the Vatican on Easter Sunday, Pope Francis has renewed his call for the release of all Israeli hostages and a ceasefire in Gaza.

title.children: Pope Francis calls for Gaza ceasefire in Easter address

image.altText: An aerial view of a beach, land, and the ocean. A vehicle is on the beach.

props.synopsis: For many generations, driving along the beach has been a cherished way of life. But with 4WD sales increasing, more Australians are reportedly driving on beaches and there's concern that's further impacting the natural dynamics of our coastlines.

title.children: Taking your 4WD to the beach? Here's how to avoid getting bogged in the soft sand

image.altText: A tray of lobster on ice

props.synopsis: While winemakers are celebrating the Chinese government's decisions to lift punishing tariffs, rock lobster producers say they aren't feeling confident about a similar move for their industry.

title.children: Rock lobster fishers 'treading water' waiting for China to lift live exports ban

image.altText: a girl smiling and wearing a floral top

props.synopsis: Forget chess and debating clubs, in an old shed in Western Australia, these county kids are competing in merino wool judging to prepare them for life on the land.

title.children: At just 17, Libby is already one of of the youngest wool judges across Australia

image.altText: A man points while a woman smiles

props.synopsis: As King Charles tries to keep an ancient institution going in a modern world, he might have to rethink his stance on the importance of history, heritage and glamour.

title.children: 'Doesn't sound like a good idea': The king's sister warned of a princess shortage long before Kate fell ill

image.altText: A woman holding a photograph f a traditional Indigenous man

props.synopsis: Sylvia Tkac was watching ABC News when she saw something shocking. Now the breakthrough identification of her great-grandfather is shedding light on a little-known chapter of Australia's history, involving international romance, mysterious gold teeth and long-lost family.

title.children: A young man's story of love and loss has solved a history mystery. It is also helping rewrite Australia's origin story

image.altText: A Cronulla NRL player celebrates after kicking the ball into the crowd.

props.synopsis: A wild game in the Shire sees the Sharks score a string of tries to earn a come-from-behind win over Canberra, after the Warriors outpoint the Knights in Auckland. Follow all the action in our live blog.

title.children: Sharks score come-from-behind win over 'embarrassing' Raiders, Warriors take down Knights

image.altText: Tim Tszyu fights Sebastian Fundora in Las Vegas

props.synopsis: Tim Tszyu's dreams of becoming a unified boxing world champion end in a bloody title fight in Las Vegas, with the Australian losing in 12 rounds to Sebastian Fundora.

title.children: Tim Tszyu loses world title in bloody Las Vegas split decision

image.altText: A young girl sitting with a basket of easter eggs

props.synopsis: Australians young and old have flocked to church services to mark Easter Sunday, and spent the morning enjoying some Easter treats.

title.children: Australians celebrate Easter Sunday, with full congregations across the country

image.altText: A Richmond player smiles in triumph as he hangs in the arms of a teammate after a goal in a big game.

props.synopsis: Richmond hangs on to beat Sydney in an MCG thriller for the Tigers' first win in 2024, after the Western Bulldogs obliterates the West Coast Eagles down the road at Docklands.

title.children: Tigers time as Richmond beat Swans in MCG thriller, Bulldogs smash struggling Eagles

image.altText: a man sits inside a nsw ambulance after being rescued from the jenolan caves

props.synopsis: The pair were among six people trekking through the Jenolan Caves in the NSW Central Tablelands on Saturday night, when they became stuck in a tight and narrow spot.

title.children: Two people trapped for 10 hours in cave freed after 'extremely difficult' rescue

image.altText: Do you know where the Monopoly boardgame comes from?

props.synopsis: Have you played Monopoly? The boardgame was designed to teach us about rents. Some economists say if we took rents seriously we could solve many problems.

title.children: What do land tax, Monopoly, and Australia have in common?

image.altText: A teenager with shirt off throws a punch with gloves on, and hits pads held by another teenager with shirt on

props.synopsis: The declaration of a two-week youth curfew in Alice Springs to curb crime and antisocial behaviour has been called a "circuit-breaker" by some and a "punitive" response by others. But one thing almost everyone agrees on is the need for medium and long-term solutions to tackle the town's issues.

title.children: Calls for long-term solutions in Alice Springs after two-week youth curfew ends

image.altText: Ute flooded in campsite

props.synopsis: A group of campers remain stranded at an outback campsite near Mount Isa, with surrounding waters set to continue rising after authorities rescued two mothers and three infants.

title.children: Outback campers wake to find their swags floating as they are cut off by Queensland flash floods

image.altText: pictures of Lesley trotter overlaid on photos of the search for her remains

props.synopsis: Lesley Trotter's disappearance sparked a large-scale search of Brisbane bushland. Then a grim discovery was made just metres from her front door.

title.children: Lesley Trotter's disappearance sparked a major search, but police would make a grim discovery closer to home

image.altText: A man sits on rocks next to a river with three emergency workers standing beside him

props.synopsis: It's believed there are many more rescues in wilderness areas than publicly reported, and experienced bushwalkers should reassess their preparation for hikes in areas affected by heavy regrowth, one experienced guide warns.

title.children: Bushwalker Andy Collins is horrified he almost made a decision that would have made his rescue a 'body recovery'

image.altText: Three people smile and pose for a photo in a dance studio, two people use a wheelchair.

props.synopsis: Dom Tulleken runs a dance academy for people with a disability. He encourages people to be their true selves — an ethos he lives by.

title.children: Dom runs a dance academy encouraging people be their true selves – it's an ethos he lives by

image.altText: Tom Gleeson standing with his arms crossed and a serious look on his face. The Hard Quiz has been added behind his head

props.synopsis: You again? Still convinced you’d outperform actual Hard Quiz contestants? We'll see about that. Let’s play…. HARD!

title.children: Think you know a thing or two about quizzes? I'll be the judge of that... Let's play, HARD!

image.altText: Humanitarian aid is airdropped to Palestinians

props.synopsis: An aid delivery in Gaza has descended into chaos with shots fired and five people reportedly killed, as almost six months of Israeli bombardment has left hundreds of thousands of civilians in desperate need.

title.children: Another aid delivery in Gaza turns deadly, as UN warns famine is imminent in northern areas

image.altText: A man grins into the camera while a car is put on a barge

props.synopsis: Matt Wright has been a powerhouse of the Top End’s tourism industry for years. But in the wake of the crash death of his Netflix co-star, some of his businesses have been folded.

title.children: Major brands put Outback Wrangler on ice in wake of crash death

image.altText: bald man with short beard wears a dark suit and glasses. he holds a hand over his chest.

props.synopsis: When Moby was last in Australia, he played the most embarrassing show of his life. The DJ and producer reflects on that gig — and the broader power of house music — with Double J's Tim Shiel.

title.children: 'Like seeing Led Zeppelin, followed by their accountant': Moby on his 'embarrassing' Australian show

image.altText: Lizzie Eastham smiles as a black dog licks her face.

props.synopsis: Lizzie Eastham was born without sight but loves to wear make up — and wants it to be more accessible for people with vision impairments.

title.children: 'Lack of sight does not mean lack of pride': People with vision impairment call for more accessible beauty products
